                        <provenance type="found" when="2021">Discovered in the fabric of Seskinan parish church (bottom of south wall) by stone mason Tom Pollard during conservation work on the ruin in 2021. The current church (WA013-034001-) was probably built on the site of an earlier church. There were traces of an ecclesiastical enclosure in the field to the south and within the graveyard (Brash 1868-9, 127; Power 1898, 84), but this is no longer evident. There is also the site of Toberatemple Well (WA013-032001-) c. 250m to the west (Power 1898, 83). The church is an undifferentiated structure (int. dims. 22.2m E-W; 7.55m N-S) surviving complete (H of long walls c. 2.1-2.5m) with quoins and a double bellcote (now damaged) over the west gable. There are pointed doorways towards the west end of the north and south walls, with a stoup inside the south doorway and an aumbry at the east end of the south wall. Two ogee-headed windows, one above the other, are in the west gable, with another in the east wall, and there are two simple lights towards the east end of the long walls. All the embrasures are lintelled internally except the east window which has a flat arch of dressed voussoirs and ingoings. The square base of a font (WA013-034004-) is also located within the church (Power 1898, 83). All of the lintels, except one over the north doorway, have ogham inscriptions (Brash 1868-9, 118-30; Macalister 1945, 286-9), and a seventh ogham stone is standing in the north-west corner of the church. An eighth ogham stone, said to have also originated here, was recorded by Macalister (1907, 213; 1945, 289) at Salterbridge House, near Cappoquin prior to 1907 but it was missing when he returned in 1940. This fragment is the ninth ogham discovery at this site.
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance type="observed">Currently in the National Museum of Ireland, Dublin.
                        </provenance>
