        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC"><!--update lang and resp here-->              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="stroke"/><damage>ᚅ</damage>ᚌ<choice><unclear>ᚒ</unclear><unclear>ᚓ</unclear><unclear>ᚔ</unclear></choice><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="stroke"/>
                </ab> 
            </div>                    
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" xml:space="preserve" resp="#POC">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="stroke"/><damage>N</damage>G<choice><unclear>U</unclear><unclear>E</unclear><unclear>I</unclear></choice><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="stroke"/>
                </ab>
                <ab type="list">[---]NGE[---]</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1"><note>Although the arris is damaged at this point, the 5 N strokes are clear and evenly spaced. If read in the opposite direction, this would be a Q, but this is unlikely next to a G. Three notches survive after the G, which could be a U or the remains of an E or I. </note>                    
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p></p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                 <p>This could be the middle part (-NGE-) of a name like DOMNGEN, which is found in an ogham inscription in Co. Cork (I-COR-021, Carhoovauler 1).</p>
            </div>
